post_text:
ELEMENTARY PARENTS: Tomorrow is the first day of school!! We have been planning for this day for almost 6 months! So here is the plan:
K-1-2 students have conferences. You have been assigned a time to meet with your teacher. The conferences last 15-20 minutes and that is their first day.
3-4 students begin at 9am and end their day at 2:30pm.
We will have people over at the high school to help the students find their way from the bus.
Our building will be open to students at 8:45am for students. Our playground is open to students at 8:30am.
Breakfast is served in the classroom at 9am for everyone.
Our playground is closed to parents. Good-byes should be said out front.
If parents need to come in to the school, an appointment should be made. 297-5500.
Please do not send your child if they are sick.
Masks are required. Mask breaks are worked into the day--for sure!!

This is a crazy time for all of us. Please know we are doing our best to keep all students and staff safe. We love our kids and teachers and do not want anyone getting sick! If you have any questions, please call us.

post_text: As the confusion on masks and case numbers continues our policy on masks has not changed. As of right now we are under our policy #4. The Governor has mandated masks in counties with 4 or more cases. Currently Lincoln County has 3 active cases therefore the Health department may change to allow less wearing of masks. I believe that after a pre-determined number of days with less than four cases the Health Department will allow us to go back to our policy‚Äôs step 1-3. I can not predict the number of cases in our county any better than anyone else can. My recommendation is to do everything you can do to keep the number of cases below 4. Social distance, hand washing , and masks are the current recommendations. Please do not comment on this post. It is information and the decision is not the school‚Äôs at this point. Please call my office on Monday if you have questions. 297-5650.

post_text: LCHS will be holding its 8th annual Freshman Academy and New Student Orientation on September 1 from 10:00am-2:00pm. This event is for all incoming freshmen as well as new students to our high school. Students will get a tour of the school, meet with school staff, get their lockers, learn about school activities, and much more. Also, students will be able to check out their Chromebook. Please bring $30 fee for the Chromebook insurance. We will also be serving pizza for lunch. Door Prizes will be given out thanks to Savvy Design Company. Please meet in the auditorium at 10:00am. All students must wear a mask and we will be practicing safe social distancing standards. Masks will be provided if you do not have one. We look forward to seeing you on the 1st. Go Lions!

post_text:
Middle School Update:
--School Starts September 2, we will have in person instruction and remote learning option. Right now we anticipate about 80% of the students on campus. We will divide each grade into three groups and they will stay with that group all day, therefore limiting exposure to all kids. They will be moving from teacher to teacher for their classes, we will disinfect between classes.

--The school day will run from 9:00-2:30, with 6 periods 45 minutes long.

--Breakfast and lunch will be served to each cohort group, kids will get their food and go to their designated area to eat. As weather permits this will be outside.

--At this time masks are not required for students and staff but are optional, we will limit large groups, but if we are passing in the hall with large groups we would put on a mask for that passing, all kids should have one available.

--JH Volleyball starts August 24

--All middle school football with start the first day of school.

--Middle School XC starts the first day of school.

--All practices will start right after school around 2:45.

post_text:
Dear Students, Staff, Parents and Eureka Community:

Since the beginning of March when school,as we knew it, was shut down the staff of Eureka Schools has been working on a plan to reopen schools. We are quickly approaching that time as we hope to start on our regularly scheduled date. We hope to release an approved plan soon. At this time I beg everyone to do their part in maintaining a healthy lifestyle to prepare our students and community for the anticipated, and needed, start of school. Things we do in the next 4-6 weeks will make a difference in our ability to have school and all our activities. Let‚Äôs work together in the hope that school can return to ‚Äúnormal‚Äù.

Join the Pride!!!
Jim Mepham, Superintendent

In order to protect the well being of our students and staff and with the goal of trying to open school on time with all students Eureka Public School‚Äôs buildings are closed to the public throughout the summer. The following exceptions to the rules are:
1. Central Office 10-2 Monday through Thursday
2. High School Office Tuesday from 8-12
3. Junior High Office Wednesday 9-12
4. Elementary Office Wednesday 10:30-12:30
Appointments are recommended. Call 297-5650 during Central Office hours for questions.

The buildings are still open for approved and staff-supervised student groups. Thank-you for helping us keep our students and staff healthy.

post_text: As the school year has come to a close, we would like to thank all the retirees of Eureka Public Schools. In total, our retirees have contributed a collective total of 166.5 years of service at Eureka Schools. Whatever their post-retirement plans, best wishes go out to each of them. Thank you for everything you have done to make our school so great! Retirees and years at Eureka include: Sue Mepham, 13 years; Chris Moen, 18.5 years; Ann Newell, 20 years; Carrie Holder, 32 years; Ed Newell, 20 years; Dennis Radish, 14 years; Jim Henrie, 25 years. post_text: The LCHS Graduation is on Saturday, May 30th at 1:00pm on the football field. We will be live streaming the graduation on this school Facebook page, as well as recording it. It will not be broadcast on the radio. Per recommendation of the county health department, we are limiting family and friends in attendance to 8 per graduate. Graduates will be sitting in the bleachers, with guests sitting on the football field. We will not be providing chairs, so please bring your own chairs to sit in. Bathrooms will not be available on campus. Let‚Äôs celebrate this senior class for all of their accomplishments. Congratulations Graduates!

post_text:
LCHS Summer Drivers Education is a go. We are starting a little later than usual, but we will be offering the class starting the first week of June. Please complete the signup form if you are interested in attending the class. We will also sign up kids at the Junior High Checkout day on May 28. We will accept up to 20 students for the class. (Oldest Students will have priority) Your birthday must be on or before December 10, 2005 to qualify for the class. Class times and days are not flexible, so we cannot work around your work schedule or vacations. The cost of the class is $250, and will be approximately 4 weeks in length. Students will each be required to have a mask while they are driving. If you have any questions, please email Ed Newell, enewell@teameureka.net, or Wade VanNess, wvanness@teameureka.net

Signup Form:
https://forms.gle/migDQWzp3uMkAHW7A

post_text: At last night‚Äôs School Board Meeting the Board of Trustees voted unanimously to continue with remote/online learning until the end of the school year. The Board did allow for possible individual and small group meetings starting after May 7. Some teachers and counselors may choose to do this. It is completely optional for both students and staff. Individual schools will let you know if this occurs via email or this web site. Thank you for all your input in this difficult decision. We know not everyone agrees with decision but be assured that the health and safety of our students and staff was the number one priority. As usual please direct any questions to individual schools or to my office at jsalyer@teameureka.net or 297-5650.

post_text: When we look back at this difficult time when the threat of COVID-19 gripped our little town, one name will be spoken as the Individual who took time to help us remember to be there for each other, to laugh, and to enjoy the things that we had control over. This individual is our Hero of the Day! Marriah Miller has spent countless hours bringing us together as a Community‚Ä¶ At a safe distance‚Ä¶ We truly appreciate her ability to look at the situation from all angles. You, Marriah, are a true hero to our community. Thank you ever so much! Your gift certificate to Cafe Jax will be hanging on the bulletin board outside the Central Office.

Lincoln County High School will be joining in with other schools to turn on the stadium lights. We will be turning on the football stadium lights tonight, Friday April 3, from 7:00 to 9:30PM as a way to honor our students, staff, and community members in this time of distance learning while school buildings are closed due to COVID-19 concerns.

These lights are a symbol of hope and an assurance that our students are in our hearts and on our minds. As anyone sees the lights, be assured that we are still there for our community and our students. No matter the struggles, Lion Nation is one big family!

post_text:
Today‚Äôs Eureka Schools Community Hero is Carri Butler. Carri has been busy helping those in our community by sewing masks for our medical staff at the clinic.
Her nomination says ‚ÄúCarri is always willing to help anyone in need. She was reached out to late Tuesday evening to see if she had a mask that could be purchased for an exchange student that was getting ready to travel home. She didn‚Äôt have any in stock but she had one made by the next morning so that our student would be safe. Not only did she do so free of charge but she made it in the students favorite color.
Carri is always willing to help anyone in need and she does so with kind words and a welcoming smile. Thank you Carri for loving our community and always being willing to help. Today‚Äôs gift card is to Route 93.

post_text:
Governor Bullock just placed the State under ‚ÄúStay-at-Home‚Äù orders. This order does not change much about the way the school is conducting business. I urge everyone to limit school visits to emergency/essential trips. Food service continues as usual and if you can not pick up please use our delivery service. Remember to call your school or your teacher with any questions. Continue getting your class assignments in and on time. Additional closures and cancellations will be posted here. Individual outdoor activities encouraged by the Governor. Hike, bike, run, or do some yard work. We don‚Äôt know anything about the future of school after this current closure but will announce as soon as we hear anything. Try to stay healthy!
Jim Mepham

Individual outdoor activities encouraged by the Governor. Hike, bike, run, or do some yard work. We don‚Äôt know anything about the future of school after this current closure but will announce as soon as we hear anything. Try to stay healthy!
Jim Mepham

post_text:
Eureka Montana Digital Academy Information for students.

MTDA High School Original Credit

High school original credit courses will remain available in our
online classrooms during the closure. We have asked all of our teachers to make sure all assignments are open for completion through April, but, at this point, we will not enforce any short-term deadlines in the course. Our teachers will be available to connect with students via email. We are also asking our teachers to continue to stay in touch with their students over the next two weeks to help provide connection and emotional support.

MTDA High School Credit Recovery

Our credit recovery program will pause until March 27, 2020, and courses themselves will be closed during that time. Please do not distribute passwords, per our school guidelines. MTDA staff will evaluate the situation daily and determine our next actions with credit recovery as the situation evolves.

Please contact your MTDA/FVCC online instructors.

post_text:
Congratulations to everyone for getting through day one of our shutdown and thanks to everyone‚Äôs dedication to our community.
1. Principals and teachers have our home bound education in place to start tomorrow. If you are unable to pick up materials tomorrow please call you school in the morning. Please get in and out of the building quickly. Do not come to school if you have an illness. Do not forget : books, computers, library books and musical instruments.
2. Our food program started preparing meals for pick-up today. Please call to place orders. Delivery can be requested.
3. Please call your school or 297-5650 with questions during our closure. Remember these phones are being answered by volunteers in their homes. Limit calls to regular school hours. Contact your teachers directly for educational questions as they direct you.
4. Remember all activities have been canceled for at least two weeks. Additional cancelations have been made. Continue to monitor our FaceBook or Webpage for details and share this information with all.
Thanks for anything you can do to help.

Attention to those students who were invited to turn in an Honor Society Application on March 30th. Due to school being cancelled, we wanted to let you know what our expectations are for the application process.
1. They are still due on March 30th by 4pm, if the date that school resumes is changed, they will be due the day we get back by 4pm.

2. If you have not gotten a transcript yet, we will get it for you, don't stress about it.

3. Do not stress about getting all the signatures for your community service hours, we do not want you to expose yourselves to people who may potentially be at risk.

4. If you have not gotten your letters of recommendation yet, have the people email them to me and I will print them out and put them with the application.

If you have any questions or concerns, please let me know by email at apacella@teameureka.net
Stay healthy and see you soon.
Mrs. Pacella

post_text: LCHS welding students Gavyn H. and Chance M. competed in a welding competition at FVCC. There were 8 schools represented with 16 competitors. Each student was given a blueprint of a project and then they had to weld it up using flat metal, pipe, and square tubing. Gavyn won the competition with the best project design and received a $500 scholarship to FVCC and also a Lincoln welding helmet valued at over $250. Chance was just outside the top 3. Great job to both students.

post_text:
Hello Everyone!

Just another reminder that Tobacco Valley Youth Baseball will be registering children ages 4 to 12 for the 2020 baseball season on March 10th and 11th at the Eureka Elementary School Library from 3:30 to 5:30. The registration fee is $35 per child. Registration closes on March 20th. If you are unable to attend either registration day, either print the attached form or pick up a blank form at the Eureka Elementary School office. Completed forms and fees can either be dropped off at the Eureka Elementary School office or mailed to:

Tobacco Valley Youth Baseball

PO Box 1038

Eureka, MT 59917



Despite our best efforts people miss the registration deadline every year, so please help us spread the word!! For more information or e-mail us at youthbaseballtobaccovalley@gmail.com.

Thanks and have a good evening!

post_text: LCHS Winter Driver's Education signup is happening this week and next week. Classes will start on February 17. If you are 14 1/2 years of age or older, you are eligible for class. Your birthday must be on or before August 26, 2005. Please see Mr. VanNess or Mr. Newell to signup. Cost is $250 (payments are accepted) and class is approximately 5-6 weeks in length. Classroom sessions are held in the mornings from 6:00am to 8:00am approximately 3 days a week and a couple of Saturday mornings. Driving is scheduled after school and weekends. We will also have a summer session that begins in May.

post_text:
ADULT ED WELDING
There are 2 different adult welding classes being offered:

Beginning Welding- for individuals who want to learn the fundamentals of welding using stick, wire, and TIG operations. Each student will practice safety and techniques used for welding various materials and joinery. (Beginning date is February 4th, 5-7 pm in welding shop for 6 weeks (2/4, 2/11, 2/18, 2/25, 3/10, 3/17), lab fee is $30.00 to cover use of materials) Limit class to 10 or fewer students.

Advanced Welding- for individuals who have previous welding skills using stick, wire, and TIG operations. Students are allowed to build projects of their choosing and use the equipment in the shop needed to complete those projects. ( Beginning date is February 19th, 5-7 pm in welding shop for 6 weeks 2/19, 2/26, 3/11, 3/18, 3/25, 4/1), lab fee is $30.00 to cover use of materials) Limit class to 10 or fewer students.

Sign up with Kim Kilroy in the Middle School Office. Any questions, please call 297-5600 or email kkilroy@teameureka.net

Thanks!

post_text: LCHS Robotics competed in Butte this past weekend. We have three new teams that are just getting things figured out, so unfortunately none of them qualified for the state tournament. We will be traveling to Helena for a second qualifying tournament on December 6th. They learned a lot at the last event and are working hard to make improvements to compete and qualify. That said, they have done an amazing job, considering their experience, and all three teams have fully functioning robotics with autonomous programming in development. Two teams were recognized with 3rd place awards in Design and Community Connections.

post_text: How does Mom and Grandma put together a beautiful Thanksgiving meal all by themselves? post_text:
Eureka Middle & High School students participate in NASA challenge celebrating the 50th anniversary of Apollo 11 landing on the moon. The challenge involved several components to simulate a lunar landing and exploration. All navigation was done from behind a curtain having to use only cameras and feedback from astronauts. Using a drone they had to transport a lunar module to it's target, then navigate a robot to release a payload onto it's target, then continue to retrieve a specified rock sample and return to base all without crossing into any craters. Their science officer then had to identify the rock sample and share facts about it.
Their outstanding team performance earned them 2nd place out of 20 teams from across the state. Congratulations!
#Apollo50 #ApolloNextGiantLeap
